> How should I cite a press release from the WMO?
**assistant**:
> When citing a press release from the World Meteorological Organization (WMO), it's important to include key details such as the organization name, the title of the press release, the date of the release, the URL if accessed online, and, if applicable, the date you accessed it. Hereâ€™s a general format you can follow in different citation styles:
> 
> **APA Style:**
> 
> World Meteorological Organization. (Year, Month Day). *Title of the press release*. URL
> 
> **Example:**
> 
> World Meteorological Organization. (2025, April 27). *WMO highlights climate change impacts in new report*. https://www.wmo.int/example-url
> 
> **MLA Style:**
> 
> World Meteorological Organization. "Title of the Press Release." *WMO*, Day Month Year, URL. Accessed Day Month Year.
> 
> **Example:**
> 
> World Meteorological Organization. "WMO Highlights Climate Change Impacts in New Report." *WMO*, 27 Apr. 2025, https://www.wmo.int/example-url. Accessed 28 Apr. 2025.
> 
> Make sure to adapt these templates according to the specific details of the press release you are using. If you have a particular citation style or other details in mind, let me know for more tailored guidance!
